---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Eyebrow from "../components/ui/Eyebrow.astro";
---

<Base
  title="Changelog · opchain"
  description="Release notes for opchain — what shipped, when, and how to migrate."
  active="/changelog"
>
  <main class="page">
    <div class="page-head">
      <Eyebrow>changelog</Eyebrow>
      <h1>Changelog.</h1>
    </div>

    <p class="lede">
      What shipped, when, and what to do about it. The skills are
      individual Markdown files; their <code>version</code> field is the
      source of truth — this page summarises across the catalog.
    </p>

    <section class="release release--current">
      <header class="rel-head">
        <span class="rel-tag">v1.3</span>
        <h2>Runtime PM, real platforms, automated releases</h2>
        <span class="rel-date">2026-05-11</span>
      </header>

      <p class="rel-summary">
        opchain v1.3 makes the v1.2 PM-MCP prose executable end-to-end,
        expands the platform menu beyond JS / Cloudflare, and ships
        <code>release-ops</code> — the 18th skill — to automate the
        "scope → /changelog → bump → ship" cadence opchain uses for itself.
      </p>

      <h3>What's new</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>The PM-MCP loop is real.</strong> v1.2 taught the skills to
          <em>describe</em> PM-tool calls; v1.3 actually invokes them. A
          concrete tool-name registry, retry / backoff, idempotency markers,
          and a deferred-action queue mean the four PM-aware skills
          (<code>app-architect</code>, <code>git-ops</code>,
          <code>deploy-ops</code>, <code>monitoring-ops</code>) can crash-restart
          mid-flow without polluting Linear / Jira / GitHub Issues.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong><code>release-ops</code> is the 18th skill.</strong> Verbs:
          <code>/release plan|draft|bump|announce|ship</code>. Reads every
          skill's checkpoint to propose the next semver, drafts the changelog
          entry from sprint outputs, atomically bumps all skill versions,
          opens a release ticket via PM-MCP, hands off to <code>git-ops</code>
          for the merge and <code>deploy-ops</code> for staging + prod.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Platform menu grew.</strong> Django + Postgres + Render,
          Rails + Postgres + Heroku, Go + Fly.io, and Rust + Axum +
          Shuttle.rs are first-class in <code>stack-forge</code>'s decision
          tree, <code>app-architect</code>'s scaffold recipes, and
          <code>deploy-ops</code>'s provider sections.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Build-time PM-MCP validator.</strong>
          <code>scripts/validate-pm-mcp.mjs</code> runs in <code>npm run prebuild</code>
          and CI; blocks the build on placeholder drift, missing protocol
          citations, or unknown tool names.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Three new scenarios</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <a href="/demo#runtime-pm-loop">Ticket → ship → incident → postmortem on one Linear thread</a>
          — the v1.3 hero. Six skills, one Linear thread, runtime PM-MCP
          end-to-end with a transient 503 mid-deploy that the deferred-action
          queue handles cleanly.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/demo#release-ops-dogfood">release-ops ships its own release</a>
          — opchain v1.3.0 shipped via opchain v1.3.0. Meta proof that the
          new skill works for any opchain-managed project.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/demo#django-render-shipped">Django + Postgres + Render, shipped by opchain</a>
          — solo founder, GitHub Issues for tracking, Render Blueprint for
          deploy. Same opchain pipeline, no Cloudflare in sight.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Configuration</h3>
      <p>
        v1.3 adds <code>tool_overrides</code> to <code>.opchain/pm.yaml</code>
        for brokered / regulated MCP environments and an
        <code>extended</code> map under <code>states</code> for deploy /
        incident workflow names. See the
        <a href="/demo#runtime-pm-loop">runtime-pm-loop scenario</a> for the
        full schema.
      </p>

      <h3>Compatibility</h3>
      <p>
        Back-compatible with v1.2. No migration steps required. The new
        validator's first run will fail-closed if any of the five PM-aware
        SKILL.md files still carry the legacy
        <code>mcp.&lt;provider&gt;.&lt;verb&gt;</code> placeholder; if you
        forked v1.2 prose, search-replace those before upgrading. Every skill
        version is in lockstep at <code>1.3.0</code>.
      </p>

      <h3>Security posture</h3>
      <p>
        The runtime PM loop is enrichment, not load-bearing — every PM-aware
        verb still completes its primary job (sprint plan / commit / deploy /
        incident open) when the MCP server is unreachable. In regulated
        environments (HIPAA / FedRAMP / CMMC), set <code>tool_overrides</code>
        in <code>.opchain/pm.yaml</code> to point each operation at the
        broker / redactor / audit-pipeline that fronts your Linear or Jira
        tenant. The <a href="/demo#mcp-enterprise-f500">F500 healthcare</a>
        and <a href="/demo#mcp-enterprise-defense">defense CMMC L3</a>
        scenarios from v1.2 remain the reference architectures.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="release">
      <header class="rel-head">
        <span class="rel-tag rel-tag--past">v1.2</span>
        <h2>PM-tool MCP integration</h2>
        <span class="rel-date">2026-05-05</span>
      </header>

      <p class="rel-summary">
        opchain v1.2 wires the skills into the PM-tool MCPs Anthropic
        ships with Claude Code. Linear, Jira, and GitHub Issues become
        first-class context for <code>app-architect</code>, <code>git-ops</code>,
        <code>deploy-ops</code>, and <code>monitoring-ops</code> — the
        ticket is the thread of execution, not a side artefact.
      </p>

      <h3>What's new</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>app-architect /discover</strong> accepts a ticket
          reference and pre-fills the interview from the ticket body +
          comments. <code>/roadmap</code> writes the sprint plan back as
          a structured comment and (optionally) creates a child ticket
          per sprint.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>git-ops /git-sync TICKET-1234</strong> reads the
          ticket, shapes the branch / commit / PR from it, and
          transitions ticket state on PR open and merge. The PR body
          is generated from ticket description, diff summary, and
          auditor + bug-check output.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>code-auditor</strong> findings post back to the
          linked PM ticket, not just the checkpoint.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>deploy-ops</strong> auto-creates a deploy ticket per
          environment, parent-linked to every commit's tickets.
          Transitions the deploy ticket through
          <em>in-progress → staging-verified → shipped</em>
          (or <em>rolled-back</em>); comments back on each linked
          ticket on prod ship.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>monitoring-ops</strong> opens an incident ticket
          when alerts fire, parent-linked to the most recent deploy
          ticket. Auto-creates remediation sub-tickets when the
          postmortem publishes.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>integrations-engineer</strong> is the canonical
          owner of the PM-MCP integration patterns; its SKILL.md
          documents detection, scoping, and audit-pipeline
          expectations for regulated environments.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Two new scenarios</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <a href="/demo#mcp-enterprise-f500">MCP at a Fortune-500 healthcare insurer</a>
          — HIPAA + ISO 27001 + SOC2 + an internal AI-Use Policy;
          custom PHI-redacting FHIR proxy MCP; SIEM-forwarded audit
          log; phased rollout with abort criteria.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/demo#mcp-enterprise-defense">MCP at a CMMC L3 defense prime</a>
          — FedRAMP High / IL5; on-prem MCP fleet; PIV/CAC-rooted
          broker; cross-domain Guard signatures for the MCP envelope;
          ATO modification package and STIG-hardened workstation
          profile.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/demo#pm-pipeline-linear">v1.2 hero scenario — Linear-led pipeline</a>
          — the full v1.2 flow on a real Linear ticket, ticket → ship
          → first incident, with Jira and GitHub Issues called out
          as one-line config swaps.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Configuration</h3>
      <p>
        v1.2 adds <code>.opchain/pm.yaml</code> at the repo root.
        Default mapping is Linear; Jira and GitHub Issues are drop-in
        with provider-specific issue-type and state mappings. See the
        <a href="/demo#pm-pipeline-linear">hero scenario</a> for the
        full schema.
      </p>

      <h3>Compatibility</h3>
      <p>
        v1.2 is backward-compatible with v1.1. Without a
        <code>.opchain/pm.yaml</code> file (or with an MCP server
        unconfigured) every skill operates as it did in v1.1; the PM
        loop is enrichment, never a hard dependency. Skills will
        prompt once on first use to write the config, then proceed.
      </p>

      <h3>Security posture</h3>
      <p>
        Regulated environments should not adopt v1.2 by default. The
        Fortune-500 and Defense scenarios document the broker /
        redactor / audit-pipeline / cross-domain rules that must
        precede any production deployment under HIPAA, FedRAMP,
        CMMC, ITAR, or equivalent regimes. v1.2 is opt-in via
        <code>.opchain/pm.yaml</code>; the regulated scenarios are
        the reference architectures for adopting it safely.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="release">
      <header class="rel-head">
        <span class="rel-tag rel-tag--past">v1.1</span>
        <h2>Stable release</h2>
        <span class="rel-date">2026-04</span>
      </header>
      <p class="rel-summary">
        Tri-agent harness across <code>app-architect</code>,
        <code>code-auditor</code>, <code>integrations-engineer</code>;
        full-pipeline flow from <code>/discover</code> to
        <code>/deploy</code>; checkpoint-protocol v1.0 across every
        skill; static Astro site; first set of six in-action
        scenarios.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="release">
      <header class="rel-head">
        <span class="rel-tag rel-tag--past">v1.0</span>
        <h2>Initial release</h2>
        <span class="rel-date">2026-02</span>
      </header>
      <p class="rel-summary">
        First public cut of the opchain skill catalog as a set of
        Markdown files installable into Claude Code. No site, no
        scenarios; just the skills.
      </p>
    </section>

    <p class="footer-note">
      Skill versions are stamped in <code>skills/&lt;name&gt;/SKILL.md</code>
      under <code>version:</code>; this page rolls them up by feature.
    </p>
  </main>
</Base>

<style>
  .page {
    max-width: 760px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 3rem 1.5rem 6rem;
  }
  .page-head { margin-bottom: 1.25rem; }
  .page-head h1 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--fs-2xl);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--text);
    letter-spacing: var(--ls-tight);
    margin: 0.5rem 0 0;
  }
  .lede { color: var(--muted); margin: 0 0 1.5rem; max-width: 42rem; }
  .lede code,
  .release code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 12px;
    background: var(--surface);
    border: 0.5px solid var(--border);
    padding: 1px 5px;
    border-radius: var(--r-xs);
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .release {
    margin-top: 2.25rem;
    padding-top: 1.5rem;
    border-top: 0.5px solid var(--border);
  }
  .release--current { border-top: 1.5px solid var(--accent); }
  .rel-head {
    display: flex;
    align-items: baseline;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }
  .rel-tag {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--fs-xs);
    letter-spacing: var(--ls-widest);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--accent);
    border: 0.5px solid var(--accent);
    padding: 2px 8px;
    border-radius: var(--r-xs);
  }
  .rel-tag--past {
    color: var(--subtle);
    border-color: var(--border);
  }
  .rel-head h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--fs-lg);
    color: var(--text);
    margin: 0;
    letter-spacing: var(--ls-tight);
    flex: 1 1 auto;
  }
  .rel-date {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--fs-xs);
    color: var(--subtle);
    letter-spacing: var(--ls-wide);
  }
  .release h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--fs-base);
    color: var(--text);
    margin: 1.25rem 0 0.4rem;
    letter-spacing: var(--ls-tight);
  }
  .release p,
  .release li {
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: var(--fs-sm);
    line-height: var(--lh-base);
  }
  .release ul {
    margin: 0.25rem 0 0 1.1rem;
    padding: 0;
  }
  .release li { margin-bottom: 0.55rem; }
  /* ADEV-342: `text-decoration: none` was previously here, overriding
     the global :where(p, li, ...) underline rule (global.css:111) and
     leaving in-prose links distinguishable only by colour — axe's
     `link-in-text-block` rule (WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color) flagged it.
     With the override removed the global rule supplies the underline;
     colour + a:hover come from the global `a` rules. */

  .footer-note {
    margin-top: 3rem;
    color: var(--subtle);
    font-size: var(--fs-xs);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    letter-spacing: var(--ls-wide);
  }
</style>
